{{further|Gettysburg Union order of battle|l1=Union order of battle}}
The '''[[Army of the Potomac]]''', initially under Maj. Gen. [[Joseph Hooker]] (Maj. Gen. [[George Meade]] replaced Hooker in command on June 28), consisted of more than 100,000 men in the following organization:<ref name=Eicher502503>Eicher, pp. 502–503.</ref>
* [[I Corps (Union Army)|I Corps]], commanded by Maj. Gen. [[John F. Reynolds]], with divisions commanded by Brig. Gen. [[James S. Wadsworth]], Brig. Gen. [[John C. Robinson]], and Maj. Gen. [[Abner Doubleday]].
* [[II Corps (Union Army)|II Corps]], commanded by Maj. Gen. [[Winfield Scott Hancock]], with divisions commanded by Brig. Gens. [[John C. Caldwell]], [[John Gibbon]], and [[Alexander Hays]].
* [[III Corps (Union Army)|III Corps]], commanded by Maj. Gen. [[Daniel Sickles]], with divisions commanded by Maj. Gen. [[David B. Birney]] and Maj. Gen. [[Andrew A. Humphreys]].
* [[V Corps (Union Army)|V Corps]], commanded by Maj. Gen. [[George Sykes]] (George G. Meade until June 28), with divisions commanded by Brig. Gens. [[James Barnes (general)|James Barnes]], [[Romeyn B. Ayres]], and [[Samuel W. Crawford]].
* [[VI Corps (Union Army)|VI Corps]], commanded by Maj. Gen. [[John Sedgwick]], with divisions commanded by Brig. Gen. [[Horatio G. Wright]], Brig. Gen. [[Albion P. Howe]], and Maj. Gen. [[John Newton (engineer)|John Newton]].
* [[XI Corps (Union Army)|XI Corps]], commanded by Maj. Gen. [[Oliver Otis Howard]], with divisions commanded by Brig. Gen. [[Francis C. Barlow]], Brig. Gen. [[Adolph von Steinwehr]], and Maj. Gen. [[Carl Schurz]].
* [[XII Corps (Union Army)|XII Corps]], commanded by Maj. Gen. [[Henry W. Slocum]], with divisions commanded by Brig. Gens. [[Alpheus S. Williams]] and [[John W. Geary]].
* Cavalry Corps, commanded by Maj. Gen. [[Alfred Pleasonton]], with divisions commanded by Brig. Gens. [[John Buford]], [[David McM. Gregg]], and [[Hugh Judson Kilpatrick|H. Judson Kilpatrick]].
* Artillery Reserve, commanded by Brig. Gen. [[Robert O. Tyler]]. (The preeminent artillery officer at Gettysburg was [[Henry Jackson Hunt|Brig. Gen. Henry J. Hunt]], chief of artillery on Meade's staff.)

During the advance on Gettysburg, Maj. Gen. Reynolds was in operational command of the left, or advanced, wing of the Army, consisting of the I, III, and XI Corps.<ref>Coddington, p. 122.</ref> Note that many other Union units (not part of the Army of the Potomac) were actively involved in the Gettysburg Campaign, but not directly involved in the Battle of Gettysburg. These included portions of the Union [[IV Corps (Union Army)|IV Corps]], the militia and state troops of the [[Department of the Susquehanna]], and various garrisons, including that at Harpers Ferry.
